shared_text:
Doug Sandifer
5 hrs ·

To all current and former players, parents and fans of the Daviess County Boys Soccer Program. We reached a milestone in the program's history this past Monday by playing our 800th game. We are also just 4 wins away from the program's 500th win. For a bit of history- James Edward Ford was the first coach from 1983-88 and guided it through the first 110 games. Jamie was also the first coach of the girl's program when they began the in 1993. Mick Lyons took over in 1989 and coached 38 games in his two year tenure. Nicholas Brake came on in 1991 and coached the Panthers for 4 seasons and 82 games, capping it off with a 1994 District Championship in his final season. I came on board as Nick's assistant in 1993 and was handed the keys for the 1995 season and have been here ever since. So many players, parents and memories over the years and games that I have been a part of. I'm sure there are other soccer programs in the state who have surpassed the 800 game mark, but I thought this was worth sharing with all who have been a part of the first 800. Here's to many more!

Congratulations to these outstanding scholars!

post_text:
GREAT NEWS - The U.S. Department of Agriculture has approved an extension of the federal Summer Feeding Program, which allows DCPS to serve breakfast and lunch meals at NO CHARGE to all children and youth age 18 and younger. This begins on Tuesday, Sept. 1. For families picking up meals through our Curbside Meal Service, you will no longer have to provide student lunch account information or pay.

Visit https://www.daviesskyschools.org/News/curbsidemealmenu#sthash.pYMGQ7Qm.dpbs to view serving schedule for each DCPS school. Families may visit whichever location is most convenient for them. Two meals will be served on Monday, Wednesday and Friday, with the "extra" meals intended for use on Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday.

NOTE: Families who need to request special accommodations for allergies etc. should contact the cafeteria manager at the school where they pick up meals. Let them know specific dietary needs and the day(s) meals will be picked up, and they will be happy to provide an appropriate meal for your child(ren).

The Daviess County Public Schools district will transition to the "Orange" status of our Stoplight Model beginning on Monday, Sept. 14. Students in preschool through Grade 8 will return to school on the A-B Schedule. Students in grades 9-12 remain on Non-Traditional Instruction. Virtual Academy students remain on their VA schedule. An information document that includes more information about all levels of the Stoplight Model and an attendance calendar for both A and B schedules is posted on our website:

https://www.daviesskyschools.org/News/update1-family-staff-info-doc#sthash.hdaMgbhl.dpbs

Thank you, Owensboro Health! The Daviess County Public Schools district was awarded a Community Health Investments grant in the amount of $34,500 to fund “The Umbrella Project – Rise Up for Resilience.”

The Umbrella Project promotes the development of positive mental health and reduces the stigma that is so often associated with mental health. The grant will support costs associated with the Rise Up for Resilience Summit, Safe Spaces and Mindful Rooms at DCPS schools.

post_text: Our Kids Need Your Help! Do you have an old laptop that is no longer being used? Or perhaps your company or the business you work for has some laptops that are no longer needed? Please consider donating old laptops to help a student stay connected with learning this school year! The DCPS Computer Operations team can convert old laptops into usable Chromebooks for our students. We will scrub the hard drive and make the appropriate updates and find a new home for your old laptop with a student who is eager to learn. Laptops may be delivered to our Central Office at 1622 Southeastern Parkway or email tech.help@daviess.kyschools.us with your contact information, and we will make arrangements to pick up your laptop(s). Thank you for your support as we work together to ensure the success of ALL children in our community!

Nomination deadline is Monday, Aug. 10 - YOU can be part of planning for the future success of our schools and students!

The Daviess County Public Schools Board of Education is accepting nominations for business/community leaders to serve on the DCPS Local Planning Committee (LPC). Members of the LPC will be responsible for the DCPS District Facility Plan and will assist in determining future school facility construction priorities and major renovation needs.

The DCPS Board of Education will select two members from nominations received to serve on the LPC. Please submit nominations, including a letter of agreement (in which nominee agrees to serve if selected) to: LPC Search, c/o Sara Harley, Daviess County Board of Education,1622 Southeastern Parkway. Nominations and letters of agreement may also be sent by email to sara.harley@daviess.kyschools.us For more information, call 270-852-7000. Include contact information for the person being nominated. Nominations must be received by Monday, Aug. 10, 2020.

post_text:
The Daviess County Public Schools district is participating in Kentucky's "Coverings for Kids" program, accepting donations of masks and face coverings to be given to students in our schools. Donations may be delivered to the Family Resource / Youth Service Center at any DCPS school or the Central Office at 1622 Southeastern Parkway.



Wearing a mask or face covering is one of the best ways to prevent the spread of the COVID-19 virus. DCPS students in grades K-12 will be required to wear masks while riding a school bus, in commons areas, or anytime social distancing of 6 feet or more is not possible. Your donation will help support our #HealthyAtSchool efforts!



Learn more about the Coverings for Kids program here: https://governor.ky.gov/coveringsforkids This site includes a summary of how DCPS will distribute masks, directions for making masks and more.



Thank you to our community partners for supporting our efforts to keep kids safe and healthy!



For more information, write to contact@dcps.org

post_text:
Daviess County High School theatre director Karen Feldhaus hosted a virtual drama camp recently. Current and future high school students joined recent graduates in online workshops exploring topics such as stage lighting, stage management, the voice and improvisation. The workshops were all facilitated by DCHS alumni.

Rebecca Volk, one of the online presenters, had this to say:
"The arts have been alive in dark times in the past and they will remain alive now. They will change and we will adjust. A pandemic doesn't mean the arts will cease to exist, we are just forced to be safer - more creative - to think outside the box. In some ways, this may be a MORE effective way to reach students as they are already so comfortable online. Kids must still feel they have a community within the arts when everything else is so up in the air. I miss the face-to-face interactions, but I am loving the new opportunities that I might not otherwise have had time for."

post_text:
Aaron Yeiser has been named instructional technology coordinator for the Daviess County Public Schools district.

In his new role, Aaron will work directly with school leaders and teachers in the area of instructional technology, coordinating efforts to maximize the instructional opportunities teachers provide to students through technology.

“My goal is to see that every student has a teacher who is well-trained in the effective use of instructional technology, and that every teacher has the tools needed to be innovative in the classroom,” Aaron said.

Aaron has served DCPS as a technology integration specialist for the past six years. In that role, he trained and supported teachers in the appropriate use of instructional technology. During that time, he was appointed as an author of the Kentucky Academic Standards for Computer Science and served as co-chairman of the oversight committee.

post_text:
Karen Alward has been named coordinator of fine and performing arts for the Daviess County Public Schools district.

In her new role, Karen will promote quality professional development, arts experiences and student products while raising awareness of the arts. Responsibilities will include advocacy, fundraising and grant planning, development of community involvement opportunities and recruitment for DCPS arts programs.

“My ultimate goal for the students of DCPS is to cultivate an arts education aimed toward the whole child and to provide inspiration and equitable cultural experiences to every child over the entire span of their school experience,” Karen said. “In order to live one’s life as if it were a work of art, one must understand and practice the arts. I hope to model this by energizing the mindset and perception of arts education through the DCPS learning community.”

text:
The Daviess County Public Schools district puts Kids First in everything we do. That commitment extends to ensuring that the children of our community - ALL children - have the opportunity to grow up in a world in which they are treated with respect, dignity and fairness. We encourage everyone to come together at 6 p.m. Friday, June 5, at Smothers Park to Stand Up for Racial Justice, Peace and Reconciliation.

FRI, JUN 5
Standing Up for Racial Justice, Peace and Reconciliation

DCPS Summer Feeding Program is open! Meals are served from 11 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. Monday, Wednesday and Friday at the locations listed below throughout the summer.

Breakfasts and lunches for two days will be provided on each of the three serving days - Monday, Wednesday and Friday - with the extra meal intended for use on Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday.

For more information or to view/download daily menu, visit https://www.daviesskyschools.org/News/summerfeeding2020-1#sthash.BBXVisF9.dpbs

Burns Elementary School – 4514 Goetz Drive

Meadow Lands Elementary – 3500 Hayden Road

Sorgho Elementary School – 5390 Kentucky 56

Daviess County High School - 4255 New Hartford Road



MOBILE ROUTES:

Gemini Drive Apartments – 2260 Carpenter Drive

Chuck Gray Court Apartments – 650 Chuck Gray Court

Towne Square Court Apartments – 4825 Towne Square Court

Town and Country Mobile Home Park – 418 Reid Road

Colony Mobile Homes – 2016 Arlington Park Boulevard

Riverbend Pointe – 501 Office Lane

Anxiety! What does it look like? What does it feel like?

If this sounds and looks like you or someone you know, help is available:
RVBH Crisis Line: Call or text 800-433-7291
Disaster Distress Helpline: 800-985-5990
Text “TalkWithUs” to 66746
Suicide Hotline: 800-273-TALK (8255)

Deaf/Hard of Hearing resources:
Text "TalkWithUs" to 66746
Use your preferred relay service to call the Disaster Distress Helpline at 1-800-985-5990
TTY 1-800-846-8517

Spanish Language assistance:
Call 1-800-985-5990 and press 2
Text "Hablanos" to 66746

The Daviess County Public Schools Board of Education will meet at 11:45 a.m. Tuesday, April 28, in a special meeting that will be available via YouTube.

Pursuant to Executive Order 2020-243 and a memorandum issued by the Finance and Administration Cabinet dated March 16, 2020, and in an effort to prevent the spread of the novel coronavirus (COVID-19), the Daviess County Board of Education will meet utilizing a video teleconference. Members of the public will not be permitted to attend the meeting in person, but are encouraged to view the meeting on the district YouTube channel – https://www.youtube.com/user/DCPSTV/live

For more information or to view an agenda for this meeting, visit https://www.daviesskyschools.org/News/boardapril28#sthash.7AzvtYOV.dpbs

shared_text:
Jake Boswell
April 10 at 11:59 AM ·

Burns Middle School Principal Dane Ferguson has been self isolating for weeks since testing positive for COVID-19. He describes how hard it's been to find energy each day.

Mr. Ferguson spoke with me from Owensboro, where he says he's been quarantined in his home since March 22. He's working with the health department now to determine when he can end the quarantine.

They came to show support last week, and Mr. Ferguson admits that he misses his Burns Middle School Daviess County Public Schools family. As he continues to improve healthwise each day, like most of us, he's looking forward to more normal times.

As parents, guardians and caregivers, we want to be responsive to the fears and concerns of our children ... even when they are not able to put those feelings into words. The National Association of School Psychologists offers these tips for helping children cope with their feelings and the changes in their lives:

https://www.nasponline.org/resources-and-publications/resources-and-podcasts/school-climate-safety-and-crisis/health-crisis-resources/helping-children-cope-with-changes-resulting-from-covid-19

Do you - or your child - need further assistance? Help is available; just reach out:
RVBH Crisis Line: Call or text 800-433-7291

Disaster Distress Helpline: 800-985-5990
Or text “Talkwithus” to 66746

Suicide Hotline: 800-273-TALK (8255)

NPR reporter Anya Kamenetz shares a wonderful article about "How to Turn Your Home Into a School ... Without Losing Your Sanity." Delightfully illustrated by LA Johnson, this is a great message for all the parents are there who are preparing for another week of Non-Traditional Instruction. Check it out here:

https://www.npr.org/2020/03/27/816575527/comic-how-to-turn-your-home-into-a-school-without-losing-your-sanity?utm_source=npr_newsletter&utm_medium=email&utm_content=20200329&utm_term=4488712&utm_campaign=best-of-npr&utm_id=17295963&orgid=

As the article says: If you need support or assistance, PLEASE reach out to your child's teacher! We are here for you!

And if you need help caring for your emotional or mental well-being during this time, help is available for that too. Please reach out!

RVBH Crisis Line: Call or text 800-433-7291

Disaster Distress Helpline: 800-985-5990

Or text “Talkwithus” to 66746

Suicide Hotline: 800-273-TALK (8255)

You're not "stuck" at home ... You are SAFE at home! Here are some tips from the Foundation for a Healthy Kentucky to ensure your family remains as safe as possible:

PREPARE: Prepare to stay at home as much as possible by purchasing only the essentials we need for a week at a time;

PROTECT: Protect others from the virus by keeping at least six feet of distance between ourselves and others outside our homes; and

DISINFECT: Use disinfectant often on the things we touch regularly, such as door knobs, cell phones, keyboards and counters.

And if you still need some reassurance? Reach out for help:

RVBH Crisis Line: Call or text 800-433-7291

Disaster Distress Helpline: 800-985-5990

Or text “Talkwithus” to 66746

Suicide Hotline: 800-273-TALK (8255)

post_text: College View Middle School staff members rallied together to create food baskets to deliver to students and families who might otherwise not have enough food on hand during the current COVID-19 situation. It wasn't easy to find groceries among all the empty shelves - but somehow they did it! Under the leadership of Youth Service Center coordinator Amy Nonweiler, the CVMS team put about 75 baskets together over the past couple of days and will team up with the DCPS Transportation Department to deliver them to students' homes today. Thank you to the CVMS team for going the extra mile for your Viking families!

Notice to the Public: The DCPS Central Office remains in operation as we work to support our students, families, community and staff.

Please understand that we must request that all non-essential business be conducted by phone or email during this time.

If you have items to drop off, you will find a convenient drop-box located next to our front door. Please put materials in an envelope addressed to approprirate person or department, and be sure to include your contact information (name, phone, email) in case we have any questions or need to follow up with you.

Our phone number is 270-852-7000. Our email address formula is firstname.lastname@daviess.kyschools.us If you do not know the name of the person you need, write to contact@dcps.org and we will forward your message to the appropriate person/department.

Thank you for your understanding and cooperation as we continue our commitment to serving the students and families of Daviess County Public Schools.

post_text: The Life Science Academy hosted Dr. Brandon Taylor and Mrs. Kimberely Taylor on Friday, Feb. 28. Dr. Taylor, a dentist at the Community Dental Clinic, talked to students about how to perform oral surgery on patients and provided several visual and hands-on examples throughout the presentation. Students practiced suturing - the process of stitching a wound after surgery - using rubber practice kits. DCPS is proud that our students are provided with these real-world learning experiences and we send sincere thanks to Dr. and Mrs. Taylor for visiting the LSA to teach and inspire our students.

Sorgho Elementary School is sponsoring its second annual Operation Warm Hands project, collecting dental hygiene items, socks and gloves that will be donated to local homeless shelters and distributed to displaced individuals in the Washington, D.C., area.

Student members of the SES Lighthouse Team will be stationed along the morning drop-off line from 7 to 7:30 a.m. Tuesday to collect items. Toothbrushes, toothpaste, dental floss, mouthwash, socks, gloves, mittens or financial donations may also be delivered to the school at 5390 Kentucky 56 anytime between 7:30 a.m. and 2 p.m. weekdays.

Operation Warm Hands is part of the school’s ongoing work in nurturing a spirit of community service among its students.

Toothbrushes, toothpaste, dental floss, mouthwash, socks, gloves, mittens or financial donations may also be delivered to the school at 5390 Kentucky 56 anytime between 7:30 a.m. and 2 p.m. weekdays.

Operation Warm Hands is part of the school’s ongoing work in nurturing a spirit of community service among its students.

Volunteers needed! Burns Middle School will host a “Reality Fair” for eighth-grade students from 8:15 a.m. to 3:10 p.m. Friday, March 27, in the BMS gymnasium. The school is located at 4610 Goetz Drive.

The Reality Fair is an opportunity for students to develop an understanding of all the expenses they must pay each month in order to successfully operation a household. Students gain insight into real life experiences as they move through the various stations, collecting paychecks, being assigned children, and managing their budgets as they navigate expenses in utilities, insurance, childcare and the ever-popular taxes at the “Uncle Sam” booth.

The event is supported by numerous community partners and parent volunteers who provide information and services at each booth. Additional volunteers are welcome and are invited to contact Victoria Self, BMS Youth Service Center coordinator, at 270-852-7411 or victoria.self@daviess.kyschools.us Lunch and snacks will be provided to all volunteers.

post_text: Sorgho Elementary School students were quick to respond when teacher Catie Bailey saw a news story about the Daviess-McLean Baptist Association being critically low on supplies in their food pantry. The Daviess-McLean Baptist Building on Lancaster Avenue is the home of our Sorgho Learning Zone, where students go after school two days a week to get homework help and a warm meal! With the help of SES Family Resource Center coordinator Lucas Vilorio, the students planned a food drive. Students and families brought in items on Valentine's Day as a way to show our love for the Daviess-McLean Baptist Center. They also delivered fliers to the neighborhood adjacent to Sorgho, telling them about our plans and giving them the opportunity to donate. Fifth-grade students walked the neighborhood last week to pick up donations. This was a great way for our students to show our love and support our local community!

post_text:
#BlackHistoryMonth
Daviess County High School's Houston Hogg was one of the first athletes to break the color barrier and play in the SEC at the University of Kentucky.

"He affected so many people off the field. It wasn’t just football, but how many people came to Houston in the African-American community at UK. They depended on Houston because he was always so giving. Whatever people needed, Houston was there." - Teammate Wilbur Hackett
Thank you, Houston Hogg, for all you have done for our world.
Mr. Hogg passed away Jan. 3, 2020, at the age of 71.
#riseup #bethe1 #dcpskidsfirst

post_text:
A community awareness program focusing on the topic of vaping is scheduled from 5:30 to 7 p.m. Thursday, Feb. 13, in the Daviess County High School media center. The school is located at 4255 New Hartford Road.

The free program is designed for DCHS students and families, but members of the public are also welcome to attend. A free dinner catered by Real Hacienda will be served. Advance registration is not required.

Parents, grandparents, caregivers and anyone concerned about the increase in vaping, e-cigarettes, Juuls and other products among our community youth is encouraged to attend. Discussion topics will include health and legal consequences of those products.

Speakers will include Rebecca Horn, health education coordinator at the Green River District Health Department; Daviess County Sheriff’s Office Deputy Paul Mattingly, who serves as DCHS School Resource Officer and DCHS administrators.

The program is presented by Daviess County High School with partnership and support of the Green River District Health Department and the Daviess County Sheriff’s Office.

post_text: The Daviess County Public Schools district is hosting an informational session for parents and families of current eighth-grade students who may be interested in pursuing dual credit opportunities in high school. The session begins at 6 p.m. Monday, Jan. 13, at Daviess County High School, 4255 New Hartford Road. Families whose students will attend either DCHS or Apollo High School are welcome. The evening will feature district representatives sharing information about the Life Science Academy, Engineering Academy, DCPS Early College Academy and Dual Credit options, in which students can earn college credit while attending high school, graduating from high school with an associate’s degree. Information about the ACT and Community Campus requirements will also be presented, with an emphasis on the ways students may prepare themselves for success in high school and beyond. Advance registration is not required. For more information, contact DCPS college and career readiness coordinator Amanda Jerome at amanda.jerome@daviess.kyschools.us or 270-852-7000.

Congratulations to the Daviess County High School CyberPatriot team for their State Championship in the National Youth Cyber Defense Competition! The team now advances to the semifinals on Jan. 25.

Teams from across the nation and world compete to identify and resolve cybersecurity vulnerabilities in simulated environments. The CyberPatriot program is designed to challenge students in the areas of cybersecurity and other science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) disciplines that are essential to the security and future of our nation.

Team captain is Micah Rice and team members are Madison Kelley, Samuel Manqueros, Shelby Taylor, John Vanover, Kali Howard and Abel Galloway. Coach is Senior Chief Michael Gatrost, who serves as Naval JROTC instructor at DCHS.

post_text:
Support our kids as they support the fight against cancer!

Apollo High School will host a DanceBlue mini-marathon from 3 to 11 p.m. Sunday, Jan. 19, in the AHS gymnasium. This seventh annual event supports the University of Kentucky’s DanceBlue Hematology/Oncology Clinic at the Kentucky Children’s Hospital in Lexington.

More than 300 students representing Apollo, Owensboro and Owensboro Catholic high schools, the Academy of Young Leaders, College View Middle School and the University of Kentucky will be on their feet and active throughout the evening as they support patients and families fighting pediatric cancer.

Guests and visitors are welcome to stop by during this event to make donations. Donations will also be accepted at Apollo High School, 2280 Tamarack Road, during regular school hours prior to Jan. 19. For more information, call 270-852-7100.

Thank you to our community sponsors and supporters who have donated dinner and snacks for participants: Subway, Domino’s, Beef O’ Brady’s, Olive Garden, Little Caesar’s, Ritzy’s and Pizza Hut.

post_text:
Want to see kids literally building their future success? Engineering Academy students will present their annual project showcase at Apollo High School on Friday, Jan. 10. Projects will be presented from 8 to 9 a.m. and from 2 to 3 p.m. in Rooms 207 and 208 at the school, located at 2280 Tamarack Road. The showcase is open to the public.

Projects demonstrating expertise in the areas of reverse engineering and robotics will be spotlighted as students describe the learning and implementation processes that were involved in creating these demonstrations.

Engineering and computer science teacher Jonathan Leohr described showcase projects that will be presented by his students: “Every year, students in the Principles of Engineering class are tasked with creating a machine that sorts marbles of different materials using VEX robotics parts. Throughout this project, students learn not only how to design, build and program, but also how to properly execute the engineering design process. Students are also learning how to create web pages in order to present their documentation.”

post_text:
Saddened to hear the news of the passing of the groundbreaking @UKFootball Player and Daviess Country High School standout Houston Hogg (DCHS Class of 1967). His contributions to the game of football will not be forgotten. #Legend #riseup #betheone

Houston Hogg, a football player who helped break the color barrier at the University of Kentucky and in the Southeastern Conference, died Thursday, Jan. 3. He was 71.

Hogg was one of four black players — along with Greg Page, Nate Northington and Wilbur Hackett — who pioneered integration at UK. The four men have been memorialized with a statue, erected in 2016, that stands outside of the Joe Craft Football Training Facility, adjacent to Kroger Field. Their trail-blazing story was chronicled in a documentary, “Black in Blue,” which debuted in a program hosted by the Foundation for DCPS. Hogg was also inducted into Owensboro's Walk of Fame in 2018. His plaque is located on the south side of Second Street, near the Judicial Center, commemorating him as one of our community's most outstanding citizens.

post_text: The Apollo High School cheerleaders made school history on Saturday, Dec. 7, as they traveled to Lexington for KHSAA state competition. The cheerleaders finished in third place just behind 17-time national champion Greenup County and five-time consecutive state champions Bullitt East High School. The third-place finish is Apollo’s highest placing ever at the state level. The cheerleaders next compete at UCA Nationals in Orlando. Congratulations, AHS Cheerleaders! Let that Eagle Spirit shine!
